-->
    
      </div>
  
  
    <h3>One Line Summary</h3>
    <div class="compressed"><p>Accelerating Platform Device Driver development using HWMODs:  Autogenerating Platform specific data &amp; simplifying module Power Management support</p></div>
  

    <h3>Abstract</h3>
    <p>The problem statement:<br />
The bus topology, device integration data &amp; power management features of the various on-chip components located in <span class="caps">OMAP</span> SOCs are complex in nature. <br />
They potentially differ across different SOCs &amp; revisions. Implementing a module device driver catering to all the <span class="caps">SOC</span> platforms requires extracting this information manually from respective Technical Reference Manuals and hard coding them as platform specific code. It also involves careful consideration of the offset differences of key registers, bit-fields etc. This process is not only time-consuming but susceptible to both programming errors as well as documentation errors in TRMs.</p>
<p>Introducing <span class="caps">HWMOD</span>:</p>
<p><span class="caps">HWMOD</span> is an hw-module abstraction framework that exploits the basic commonality between the <span class="caps">OMAP</span> SOCs &amp; attempts to address the above problem through a mix of automation and optimized s/w framework.</p>
<p><span class="caps">HWMOD</span> Scripts:</p>
<p>The various hardware module data is generated automatically from the TI hardware database using suitable scripts called <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> scripts. They create constant structures &amp; headers in a standard format to manage information about <span class="caps">OMAP</span> on-chip components (&#8220;hardware modules&#8221;) and their integration to the rest of the chip. The output can be easily plugged into the driver code.<br />
The key information auto generated is:<br />
	Module Base address<br />
	<span class="caps">DMA</span> request lines<br />
	IRQs<br />
	The main clock &amp; optional clocks used by the module<br />
	<span class="caps">PRCM</span> register offset information for activating/deactivating a module.<br />
	Bus topology information of the module relative to the rest of <span class="caps">SOC</span>.</p>
<p>As <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> works in sync with the Clock Framework, therefore the clock-database structures too are generated automatically using the same scripts.</p>
<p>As the files are generated directly from the database, scope of error is eliminated.</p>
<p>Thus, this method eases segregation of driver code from platform specific details and reduces porting effort across <span class="caps">SOC</span> revisions as well as different/future SOCs.</p>
<p><span class="caps">HWMOD</span> Framework s/w:<br />
The various auto-generated data headers and constants are utilized by a layer of generic framework software called the <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> framework layer. This layer populates the Platform-resource information using the hwmod data so that they can be extracted via platform-resource APIs.<br />
<span class="caps">HWMOD</span> framework also provides APIs to enable/disable/idle a hwmod. Thereby, it encapsulates all the common code pertaining to generic module Power Management.</p>
<p>To effectively utilize the <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> layer, another layer, called the <span class="caps">OMAP</span> device layer is written on top of the <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> to provide device level enable/disable/idle APIs.<br />
The device drivers are intended to call the <span class="caps">OMAP</span>-device layer APIs only or APIs built on top of it via Runtime PM.<br />
<span class="caps">HWMOD</span> is designed to fit easily within the Linux Runtime PM framework via the Platform Bus. Platform bus implementation for <span class="caps">OMAP</span> calls the <span class="caps">OMAP</span> device APIs.</p>
<p>To exploit the <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> framework, a driver must be written as a platform-device driver. We intend to convert most of the device drivers to platform device drivers and then all the platform device drivers are to use Runtime PM so that migration to hwmod becomes seamless.</p>
<p>What is in the Presentation:<br />
In this presentation, we intend to discuss on<br />
	<span class="caps">HWMOD</span> concepts in detail<br />
Migration steps needed by a Device Driver to adopt <span class="caps">HWMOD</span>.<br />
	How <span class="caps">HWMOD</span> interfaces with Runtime PM<br />
Benefits achieved within TI by taking the hwmod approach in terms of the development effort saved.</p>
<p>This presentation will potentially interest people who are trying to solve similar scalability problems across different platforms especially in areas of Power Management.</p>
<p><span class="caps">HWMOD</span> conversion of the device drivers is currently in progress on TI <span class="caps">OMAP</span> 3 &amp; 4 processors.</p>
<p>Acknowledgements: <br />
Paul Walmsley [<a href="mailto:paul@pwsan.com">paul@pwsan.com</a>] &amp; Benoit Cousson [<a href="mailto:b-cousson@ti.com">b-cousson@ti.com</a>] who are the key authors of the framework.</p>
<p>Kevin Hilman[<a href="mailto:khilman@deeprootsystems.com">khilman@deeprootsystems.com</a>]<br />
Rajendra Nayak [<a href="mailto:rnayak@ti.com">rnayak@ti.com</a>]<br />
Sripathi Vishwanath[<a href="mailto:vishwanath.bs@ti.com">vishwanath.bs@ti.com</a>]<br />
Santosh Shilimkar[<a href="mailto:Santosh.shilimkar@ti.com">Santosh.shilimkar@ti.com</a>]<br />
Thara Gopinath[<a href="mailto:thara@ti.com">thara@ti.com</a>]<br />
Arce Abraham[x0066660]<br />
Varadarajan Charulatha[<a href="mailto:charu@ti.com">charu@ti.com</a>]</p>
<p>as the other key contributors.</p>

  

  

  

